---
import MainLayout from "../layouts/MainLayout.astro";
import { siteConfig } from "../config/site";
---

<MainLayout
  title={`${siteConfig.siteName} | Hire a logo designer without wasting money`}
  description={siteConfig.siteDescription}
  pathname="/"
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">Start here</p>
    <h1>Hire a logo designer without wasting money.</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      Write a better brief, compare your options, and know what files to ask for
      before you pay. This site exists to help you make a smarter logo decision,
      not a rushed one.
    </p>
    <div class="button-row">
      <a class="button" href="/logo-brief-template/">Use the brief template</a>
      <a class="button-secondary" href="/ai-vs-fiverr-vs-agency/">Compare your options</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="card-grid">
      <article class="card">
        <p class="eyebrow">Step 1</p>
        <h2>Write a better brief</h2>
        <p>
          Most bad logo outcomes start with a vague brief. Start with a structure
          that helps a designer understand your business, audience, style, and
          deliverables.
        </p>
        <p><a href="/logo-brief-template/">Open the template →</a></p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <p class="eyebrow">Step 2</p>
        <h2>Choose the right path</h2>
        <p>
          AI, Fiverr, and agencies can all be the right answer depending on your
          budget, speed, and brand stakes.
        </p>
        <p><a href="/ai-vs-fiverr-vs-agency/">See the comparison →</a></p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <p class="eyebrow">Step 3</p>
        <h2>Know what to ask for</h2>
        <p>
          A logo is not just a picture file. Ask for the right deliverables so
          you do not end up paying twice later.
        </p>
        <p><a href="/what-files-should-i-ask-for/">See the file checklist →</a></p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section two-col">
    <div class="soft-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Quick decision guide</p>
      <h2>Which route fits you?</h2>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Option</th>
            <th>Best when</th>
            <th>Not ideal when</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>AI</td>
            <td>You need something fast and very cheap.</td>
            <td>You want custom thinking or strong refinement.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Fiverr</td>
            <td>You want a human designer on a smaller budget.</td>
            <td>You want deep brand strategy.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Agency</td>
            <td>Your brand matters a lot and budget is larger.</td>
            <td>You only need a basic starter logo.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p style="margin-top:16px;"><a href="/ai-vs-fiverr-vs-agency/">Read the full comparison →</a></p>
    </div>

    <div class="soft-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Avoid these mistakes</p>
      <h2>Common ways buyers waste money</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li>Starting without a real brief</li>
        <li>Paying before deliverables are clear</li>
        <li>Forgetting vector/source files</li>
        <li>Picking based on style alone</li>
        <li>Not thinking about logo usage first</li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top:16px;"><a href="/logo-designer-red-flags/">See the red flags →</a></p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">Best place to start</p>
      <h2>If you do one thing first, do this.</h2>
      <p>
        Use the logo brief template before you compare designers. A better brief
        usually improves the result more than spending blindly.
      </p>
      <p><a class="button" href="/logo-brief-template/">Start the brief template</a></p>
    </div>
  </section>
</MainLayout>
